It was alſo obſerved that the Power of Viſitation is, by the Common Law, expreſsly limited to the Statutes of the Founder; 
               Lord Raymond's Reports, Vol. I. P. 7.
                which are the Conditions or Limitations of the Uſe of the Founder's Donation; and the Viſitor can do nothing but rectify thoſe Things which are plainly repugnant to thoſe Limitations; or claim a Forfeiture. But as no ſuch Statutes, made by the General Aſſembly, can be found; ſuch Viſitors would have no Power at all, or be altogether arbitrary, like the Viſitors ſent to Magdalen College, by King James II.
